50|$|Topology is {{insensitive}} {{to the details of}} a scalar field, and can often be determined using simplified calculations. Scalar fields such as electron density, Madelung field, covalent field and the electrostatic potential can be used to model topology. Each scalar field has its own distinctive topology and each provides different information about the nature of <b>chemical</b> <b>bonding</b> and structure. The analysis of these topologies, when combined with simple electrostatic theory and a few empirical observations, leads to a quantitative model of localized <b>chemical</b> <b>bonding.</b> In the process, the analysis provides insights into the nature of <b>chemical</b> <b>bonding.</b>|$|R
